<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="536">Types Mus. Civ. Stor. Nat. Genova.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="etymology">
<paragraph pageNumber="536">
Etymology L 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181962" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole capillata Emery" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole capillata Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="536" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capillata">capillata</taxonomicName>
, hairy.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageNumber="536">
diagnosis Close to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33757" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole gertrudae Forel" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole gertrudae Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="536" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gertrudae">gertrudae</taxonomicName>
(q.v.), and possibly synonymous with it, but differing in the following combination of traits.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="536">Major: propodeal spines present but only as short, thick denticles; frontal lobes covered by longitudinal carinulae; and thinner petiolar</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="536">node in side view.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="536">Measurements (mm) Lectotype major: HW 1.56, HL 1.60, SL 0.84, EL 0.22, PW 0.74. Paralectotype minor: HW 0.64, HL 0.70, SL 0.78, EL 0.14, PW 0.42.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="536">color Major: body mostly light yellowish brown with a slight reddish tint; gaster medium yellowish brown with reddish tint to plain medium brown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="536">Range Goias and Mato Grosso, Brazil; and Madre de Dios and San Martin, Amazonian Peru.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageNumber="536">
biology At Cuzco Amazonico, near Puerto Maldonado, Madre de Dios, Peru, Stefan Cover and John Tobin found a population of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181962" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole capillata Emery" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole capillata Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="536" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capillata">capillata</taxonomicName>
colonies in a grassy clearing on the Madre de Dios River. The nests were in heavy clay, and the workers were observed foraging on cloudy days and at dawn and dusk. The species was absent from the adjacent rainforest.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
